Experiment Title

Advanced Remote Control of a Stepper Motor Using Arduino MKR WiFi 1010,
 ULN2003 Driver, and Blynk IoT

Components Used

1. Arduino MKR WiFi 1010

The Arduino MKR WiFi 1010 is a microcontroller board with built-in Wi-Fi
 connectivity. It acts as the central controller, receiving commands from the
  Blynk application and controlling the stepper motor's movement and speed.

2. 28BYJ-48 Stepper Motor

The 28BYJ-48 is a stepper motor capable of precise rotational movement. Unlike a
 DC motor, it moves in fixed steps, allowing accurate control of position and
  rotation angle. In this experiment, it rotates by different step values based
   on user commands from the Blynk app.

3. ULN2003 Motor Driver Module

The ULN2003 driver serves as an interface between the Arduino and the stepper motor.
 It supplies the required current to the motor and protects the microcontroller
  from excessive current draw.

4. Blynk IoT Application

Blynk is a cloud-based IoT platform that enables remote control of electronic
 devices through a smartphone. Multiple buttons and a slider were used in this
  experiment to control the motor's rotation and speed.

5. Wi-Fi Network

The Wi-Fi network connects the MKR WiFi 1010 to the internet, allowing
 communication with the Blynk cloud server and remote operation of the motor.

6. WiFiNINA Library

This library enables the MKR WiFi 1010 to connect to Wi-Fi networks and maintain
 internet communication.

7. BlynkSimpleWiFiNINA Library

This library handles communication between the Arduino board and the Blynk IoT
 platform.

8. Stepper Library

The Stepper library provides functions for controlling the motor's rotational
 speed and movement in steps.

9. Blynk Widgets

The following widgets were used:

V0 Button: Rotate motor 100 steps clockwise.
V1 Button: Rotate motor 100 steps counter-clockwise.
V2 Button: Rotate motor 512 steps clockwise (approximately 90°).
V3 Button: Rotate motor 1024 steps clockwise (approximately 180°).
V4 Button: Rotate motor 2048 steps clockwise (one full revolution).
V5 Slider: Adjust motor speed dynamically.

What the Experiment Did

This experiment demonstrated advanced remote control of a stepper motor using
 the Blynk IoT platform.

The Arduino MKR WiFi 1010 connected to a Wi-Fi network and established
 communication with the Blynk cloud using an authentication token.
  Through the Blynk mobile application, users could remotely command the
   stepper motor using several buttons and a speed control slider.

The buttons performed different motor movements:

Pressing V0 rotated the motor 100 steps clockwise.
Pressing V1 rotated the motor 100 steps counter-clockwise.
Pressing V2 rotated the motor 512 steps, approximately a quarter turn.
Pressing V3 rotated the motor 1024 steps, approximately a half turn.
Pressing V4 rotated the motor 2048 steps, which corresponds to one complete
 revolution.

The V5 slider allowed the user to change the motor speed in real time.
 Whenever the slider value changed, the motor speed was updated using the
  setSpeed() function, and the selected speed was displayed on the Serial Monitor.

This setup enabled precise control of both the motor's position and rotational
 speed from a smartphone.

Importance of the Experiment

This experiment is important because it combines IoT technology with motion
 control systems, demonstrating how smart devices can remotely manage mechanical
  movement.

The experiment helped in understanding:

IoT-based remote control using Blynk.

Wireless communication between a mobile application and a microcontroller.

Stepper motor operation and positioning control.

Real-time speed adjustment of motors.

Integration of sensors, actuators, microcontrollers, and cloud platforms.

Such technologies are commonly used in:

Industrial automation
Smart manufacturing systems
Robotic arms
CNC machines
Automated doors and gates
Smart home systems
Camera positioning systems

The ability to control motor position and speed remotely is a key requirement in
 many modern automation applications.

4. Conclusion

The experiment successfully demonstrated remote control of a 28BYJ-48 stepper
 motor using an Arduino MKR WiFi 1010, ULN2003 motor driver, and the Blynk IoT
  platform. Different Blynk buttons were used to rotate the motor by specific
   step amounts, while a slider allowed real-time speed control. The project
    provided practical experience in IoT communication, cloud-based device
     management, motor control, and automation. Overall, the experiment
      showed how internet-connected systems can provide precise and
      flexible control of mechanical devices, forming the foundation
       for advanced smart automation and robotics applications.